00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:25.030
&gt;&gt; She was also really adamant that
the Coolidge Auditorium be wired

00:51:25.030 --> 00:51:30.330
for radio broadcast because she
wanted the concerts to be heard

00:51:30.330 --> 00:51:32.220
from everyone's living room.

00:51:32.220 --> 00:51:34.990
Yu didn't have to be
here to listen to it

00:51:34.990 --> 00:51:37.160
and that was met with opposition.

00:51:37.160 --> 00:51:42.270
But she fought for it and she
won and we have a transcript

00:51:42.270 --> 00:51:47.020
across the street in the exhibit
of a little speech she gave

00:51:47.020 --> 00:51:50.260
on the radio before a radio
broadcast and she said,

00:51:50.260 --> 00:51:53.930
"I have two things to say
to all of the, you know,

00:51:53.930 --> 00:51:55.790
listeners who've written.

00:51:55.790 --> 00:51:57.090
Thank you."

00:51:57.090 --> 00:51:58.390
And she says this lovely thing.

00:51:58.390 --> 00:52:02.720
She says, "To NBC, I
say, 'I told you so'."

00:52:02.720 --> 00:52:07.380
&gt;&gt; The other story we heard
growing up was that she would sit

00:52:07.380 --> 00:52:09.610
in the Coolidge Auditorium
with a huge;

00:52:09.610 --> 00:52:13.200
I don't know what you would call
it, a trumpet thing to her ear

00:52:13.200 --> 00:52:15.790
because she was practically deaf.

00:52:15.790 --> 00:52:18.060
You know, then she
would sit in the front.

00:52:18.060 --> 00:52:20.560
She was quite a figure
sitting there.

00:52:20.560 --> 00:52:27.320 position:56%
&gt;&gt; One thing that my mother told me,
which I don't know how true it is.

00:52:27.320 --> 00:52:31.380
I know Cyrilla touched on it
but which really impressed me.

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:34.950
She actually did not --
my mother said this now,

00:52:34.950 --> 00:52:37.180
it needs to be verified.

00:52:37.180 --> 00:52:40.920
She really didn't like
contemporary music, Chamber music,

00:52:40.920 --> 00:52:45.720
really didn't like it, but
said you have to invest;

00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:48.030
you have to support the art form.

00:52:48.030 --> 00:52:52.100
And I've heard people say that
she was called the fairy godmother

00:52:52.100 --> 00:52:53.400
of chamber music.

00:52:53.400 --> 00:52:58.660
I think, I don't know where and
if -- how broadly that was used.

00:52:58.660 --> 00:53:02.980
But -- and I was her -- because I
have some of her musician friends,

00:53:02.980 --> 00:53:06.970
who were just blown away
by what they played so many

00:53:06.970 --> 00:53:12.170
of the compositions she had done
and she really saved chamber music

00:53:12.170 --> 00:53:14.790
by supporting the new art form.

00:53:14.790 --> 00:53:16.400
&gt;&gt; I'll add two things to that.

00:53:16.400 --> 00:53:18.800
At this letter at the
top it says DFQ

00:53:18.800 --> 00:53:21.380
and that stands for
Dear Fairy Queen.

00:53:21.380 --> 00:53:27.130
And then the other thing about
new music, we include this quote.

00:53:27.130 --> 00:53:29.870
It's my favorite quote that
I found in doing the research

00:53:29.870 --> 00:53:32.250
and this is included in the
introduction across the street,

00:53:32.250 --> 00:53:35.900
but Mrs. Coolidge wrote
and said in a speech once,

00:53:35.900 --> 00:53:39.530
'My plan for modern music is
not that we should like it,

00:53:39.530 --> 00:53:43.110
not necessarily that we
should even understand it

00:53:43.110 --> 00:53:47.670
but that we should exhibit it as
a significant human document'.

00:53:47.670 --> 00:53:49.850
I think that's pretty amazing.

00:53:49.850 --> 00:53:56.730
&gt;&gt; Yeah, can ask about maybe
addressing you two as well as,

00:53:56.730 --> 00:54:02.010
I guess, Greg was your grandfather
than, about the music in the family

00:54:02.010 --> 00:54:07.850
and what the legacy of the music
actually, you know, playing and.

00:54:07.850 --> 00:54:12.150
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Thanks.

00:54:13.830 --> 00:54:17.230
My sister and I play
the guitar and sing

00:54:17.230 --> 00:54:20.960
but I grew up folk music and yeah.

00:54:20.960 --> 00:54:23.920
I really had no classical
training what so ever.

00:54:23.920 --> 00:54:25.220
I grew up hearing it.

00:54:25.220 --> 00:54:30.080
My grandfather and his wife, my
grandmother, played quartets all

00:54:30.080 --> 00:54:34.120
of the time and would meet
with people, informal quartets.

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:37.560
He -- I was told -- couldn't
judge it at the time.

00:54:37.560 --> 00:54:41.620
He was a scientist, a
chemist, at Harvard.

00:54:41.620 --> 00:54:42.920
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:54:42.920 --> 00:54:45.180
&gt;&gt; Oh, we'll talk.

00:54:45.180 --> 00:54:49.120
&gt;&gt; And he apparently played
like a scientist, very exact.

00:54:49.120 --> 00:54:52.030
He was really quite a ridged guy.

00:54:52.030 --> 00:54:56.340
I think, you know, another side
of Mrs. Coolidge is she sent him

00:54:56.340 --> 00:54:58.270
to a school when he
was really young.

00:54:58.270 --> 00:55:03.100
Not sure how much nurturing he
got, I'm sure he was loved but,

00:55:03.100 --> 00:55:05.680
you know so, anyway,
that's my memory.

00:55:05.680 --> 00:55:06.980
Do you, Joe?

